Background: Computer Science (CS) industry internships are valuable experiences for undergraduate CS students, and internship participation is predicted by extracurricular participation. Purpose : We seek to understand the specific extracurricular activities (ECAs) that are predictive of securing an internship. % to help identify what activities students can do to help them get internships. Methods: We used linear probability models to analyze survey responses from 14,155 undergraduate CS majors. We examine the relationships between students' internship participation, background, and participation in seven ECAs. Findings: All seven ECAs increased the predicted probability of internship participation (p < .05). We found no differences in internship participation by gender, race, or ethnicity. Students who were first-generation college students, non-U.S. citizens, or disabled were predicted to have a statistically significantly lower probability of attaining an internship. Students who identified as women, non-binary, Asian, and/or Black were predicted to have a statistically significantly higher probability of participating in ECAs when compared to white or male students, while students with lower GPAs or first-generation status had a lower probability. Implications: Our work uncovers inequities, particularly for first-generation college students, and provides insights that are relevant for students seeking internships.